STEP 1 — Create local project

Open terminal:

mkdir newpipeline

cd newpipeline

STEP 2 — Create website file

echo "<h1>CodePipeline MCA Lab</h1>" > index.html

STEP 3 — Verify file exists

ls

You must see:

index.html

STEP 4 — Push code to GitHub

Initialize git

git init

git add .

git commit -m "first commit"

Create GitHub repo

Repository name:

Newpipeline

Connect repo

git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/Newpipeline.git

If origin exists:

git remote set-url origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/Newpipeline.git

Push

git branch -M main

git push -u origin main

STEP 5 — Create Amazon S3 bucket

Bucket name example:

newpipelinedemo

Region:

same as pipeline region.

STEP 6 — Disable block public access

Permissions → Edit

Uncheck all 4 boxes.

Type:

confirm

Save.

STEP 7 — Add bucket policy

Paste exact policy:

{

 "Version": "2012-10-17",

 "Statement": [

 {

 "Effect": "Allow",

 "Principal": "*",

 "Action": "s3:GetObject",

 "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::newpipelinedemo/*"

 }

 ]

}

Bucket name must match exactly.

STEP 8 — Enable static website hosting

Properties → Static website hosting

Enable:

Index document = index.html

Save.

STEP 9 — Upload index.html manually first

Upload file:

index.html

STEP 10 — Verify website manually

Open website endpoint:

http://newpipelinedemo.s3-website-eu-north-1.amazonaws.com

You should see:

<h1>CodePipeline MCA Lab</h1>

STEP 11 — Create AWS CodePipeline

Source stage

Provider:

GitHub

Repository:

Newpipeline

Branch:

main

Skip build stage

Choose:

Skip build stage

Deploy stage

Provider:

S3

Bucket:

newpipelinedemo

Very important

Enable:

Extract file before deploy = ON

STEP 12 — Run pipeline

Pipeline starts automatically.

Stages:

Source → Deploy

must turn green

STEP 13 — Test automatic deployment

Change file locally:

nano index.html

Change:

<h1>Version 2 Pipeline Success</h1>

Save.

Push again

git add .

git commit -m "version 2"

git push

STEP 14 — Verify auto deploy

Refresh website endpoint.

Now you must see:

<h1>Version 2 Pipeline Success</h1>

This proves CI/CD complete

Because:

One git push automatically changed production website.
